## auditd capture ruleset for the guide — SIEM-tier Linux sensor.
## Load ad-hoc:   sudo auditctl -R labs/linux/audit.rules
## Persist:       copy to /etc/audit/rules.d/guide.rules && sudo augenrules --load
## Inspect:       sudo ausearch -k <key> --start recent -i
##
## ─── READ THIS FIRST — auditd does not "just work" ───────────────────────────
## • NOT ON BY DEFAULT. auditd is *not installed* on Ubuntu/Debian/most cloud AMIs
##   (`apt install auditd`); on RHEL/Fedora the `audit` package is installed AND the
##   service runs by default. "We see no Linux persistence/privesc" on an Ubuntu box
##   is almost always *no sensor*, not *no threat* — the guide's recurring blind spot.
## • Confirm it is actually capturing:  sudo auditctl -s   (enabled 1, pid != 0)
##   and that rules loaded:             sudo auditctl -l
## • The kernel audit backlog drops events under load (see -b / -f below); a missed
##   event is indistinguishable from "didn't happen" — tune -b up for capture runs.
## • `-w` does NOT expand globs or `~`. You cannot watch "every user's ~/.bashrc"
##   with one rule — see the LOGIN/SHELL section for the per-user caveat.
## • The `-C uid!=euid` field comparison needs a reasonably recent audit userspace
##   (auditctl ≥ 2.x); on ancient distros the privesc rule silently fails to load —
##   check `auditctl -l` shows it after loading.

-D
## bigger backlog for capture runs (default 8192 drops under burst)
-b 16384
## printk on backlog full, so you SEE drops instead of losing events silently
-f 1

## ─── EXECUTION (Part I) ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## RULE ORDERING — auditd evaluates syscall rules first-match-wins, so the SPECIFIC
## execve rules (uid!=euid privesc, pkexec execute-watch) MUST come BEFORE the broad
## -k exec catch-all below. Otherwise the general rule matches first and the event is
## tagged key=exec, never key=privesc (verified live: a uid=1000/euid=0 SUID exec was
## keyed `exec` when the catch-all preceded it, so `ausearch -k privesc` saw nothing).
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve,execveat -C uid!=euid -k privesc
-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve,execveat -C uid!=euid -k privesc
-w /usr/bin/pkexec -p x -k privesc
## Catch-all execve+execveat (32/64-bit). execveat covers fexecve / memfd anon-exec, but
## the EXECVE record can TRUNCATE long argv — the documented SIEM blind spot vs eBPF/ESF.
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve,execveat -k exec
-a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S execve,execveat -k exec

## In-memory / fileless (T1620): anonymous in-mem file then exec. auditd has no clean
## "memfd" event — it shows up only as an execve/execveat whose path is empty/anonymous
## (name resolves to 'memfd:… (deleted)'). The argc==0 / empty-path tell is fragile at
## this tier; the eBPF trace (bpftrace/memfd-exec.bt) is the authoritative sensor.
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S memfd_create -k memfd

## ─── PRIVILEGE ESCALATION (Part III) ─────────────────────────────────────────
## setuid/sudo euid→0 AT EXEC: catch execve where the real uid differs from the
## effective uid. NOTE: this is the *only* SIEM-tier signal for SUID/GTFOBins abuse,
## and it does NOT cover the capability path (cap_setuid → in-process setuid(0) with
## no exec) — that is eBPF-only. Requires auditctl with -C inter-field comparison.
## (Defined in the EXECUTION block above, ahead of the -k exec catch-all — see the RULE
##  ORDERING note; placed here, after -k exec, the catch-all would shadow it: key=exec.)
## PolKit / PwnKit (CVE-2021-4034): pkexec is SUID-root, so a normal pkexec run ALREADY trips
## the uid!=euid rule above — that tells you pkexec executed, NOT that it was exploited. The
## PwnKit tell is the exploit's own shape: pkexec invoked with argc==0 (no argv[0]) so its
## out-of-bounds argv read reaches an attacker-set environ slot, with a GCONV_PATH= entry
## pointing at a writable dir holding a malicious gconv module + a crafted gconv-modules file.
## This -w execute watch records the pkexec EXECVE/SYSCALL so you can anchor on it.
## ANCHOR NOTE (matches the §6 02-polkit fix): characterize PwnKit on the SYSCALL record —
##   comm:'pkexec' (or exe|endswith '/pkexec') AND argc:0
## Do NOT anchor on `a0|endswith '/pkexec'` AND argc==0 together: argc==0 means there IS no
## a0, so the two are mutually exclusive and the pair never matches. The argv[0] is absent on
## the SYSCALL record's argc, not present on the EXECVE record. The writable-dir GCONV_PATH
## file write is the EDR-tier corroborator (file-modify.bt / a -w on the drop dir) and only
## fires on an UNPATCHED pkexec — a patched pkexec aborts on argc==0 before iconv() loads it.
## (the -w pkexec execute-watch is defined in the EXECUTION block above, ahead of -k exec.)
## A new SUID/SGID binary being created (chmod u+s / g+s) — MITRE T1548.001 analytic.
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chmod,fchmod,fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=4294967295 -k suid_change

## ─── LOADER HIJACK (Part I ch.2) ─────────────────────────────────────────────
## /etc/ld.so.preload is a specific file → -w works. The PATH record shows the inode
## was modified, NOT the content written — pair with a file-integrity tool to see what
## was added. The per-process LD_PRELOAD env var is NOT here: it is not in the EXECVE
## argv unless passed via an `env VAR=… cmd` wrapper; the inherited form needs eBPF.
-w /etc/ld.so.preload -p wa -k ld_preload

## ─── PERSISTENCE: service / scheduled / login config writes (Part II) ─────────
## DIRECTORIES need `-F dir=` (recursive), NOT `-w` (which watches only the dir inode
## and misses file creates inside it). perm=wa = write+attr-change.
-a always,exit -F dir=/etc/systemd/system/ -F perm=wa -k svc_unit
-a always,exit -F dir=/usr/lib/systemd/system/ -F perm=wa -k svc_unit
-a always,exit -F dir=/etc/cron.d/ -F perm=wa -k cron
-a always,exit -F dir=/var/spool/cron/ -F perm=wa -k cron
## crontab(1) installs via a temp file + rename() onto the spool path, so the event may
## record nametype=NORMAL/RENAME rather than CREATE — match WRITE, not CREATE-only.
-w /etc/crontab -p wa -k cron
-a always,exit -F dir=/etc/profile.d/ -F perm=wa -k login_hook
-w /etc/rc.local -p wa -k login_hook
## sudoers tamper (NOPASSWD / !tty_tickets — Dok/Proton class).
-w /etc/sudoers -p wa -k sudoers
-a always,exit -F dir=/etc/sudoers.d/ -F perm=wa -k sudoers

## ─── PER-USER rc / XDG autostart — THE GLOB LIMITATION ───────────────────────
## auditd CANNOT watch "~/.bashrc for all users" — no globbing, no ~ expansion. Options:
##  (a) add an explicit -w per home you care about (shown for root + one lab user), or
##  (b) watch /home recursively (-F dir=/home -F perm=wa) — VERY noisy, lab-only.
## rc files already EXIST, so the attack APPENDS — a create-only sensor misses it;
## -p wa catches the write. (The EDR equivalent is bpftrace/file-modify.bt.)
-w /root/.bashrc -p wa -k login_hook
-w /root/.profile -p wa -k login_hook
## -w /home/<labuser>/.bashrc -p wa -k login_hook      ## add per real user
## -a always,exit -F dir=/home -F perm=wa -k login_hook ## (b) noisy catch-all, lab only

## Make rules immutable (requires reboot to change). Leave commented while iterating.
# -e 2
